    <h2>How does this work?</h2>
  <!--change this later!--->
      <p>
        We used <a href=https://www.kaggle.com/yamaerenay/ico-coffee-dataset-worldwide?select=domestic-consumption.csv><b>ICO's Coffee Dataset</b></a>, 
        which contains data collected about the consumption of coffee in thousand 60 kilogram bags per country. 
        We also used <a href=https://www.kaggle.com/skylord/covid19-tests-conducted-by-country><b>OurWorldInData's COVID-19 dataset</b> </a> for the number of positive COVID-19 cases per country.
        Lastly, we used <a href=https://www.kaggle.com/ajaypalsinghlo/world-happiness-report-2021?fbclid=IwAR3I5qZ6f7-1FSrkhapd5CcN-Va_iN80KIjlW9oyn8-d3u0z04GYJV1PFzU&select=world-happiness-report-2021.csv><b>World Happiness Report 2021</b></a> and
        <a href=https://www.kaggle.com/njlow1202/world-happiness-report-data-2018><b>the World Happiness Report 2018</b> </a>for information about how each country scores in keeping its citizens happy
        Take a look at what happens behind-the-screen:

        <ol>
          <li>We treat this data as our training data, and use it train a decision tree regressor, a type of machine learning algorithm.
            Check out more about Scikit-learn's awesome <a href="https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.tree.DecisionTreeRegressor"> decision tree regressors.</a></li>
          <li>Next, we read in the user's two input parameters: Coffee Consumption, Positive/Tested % (i.e. percent of total tests which are positive for COVID-19) </li>
          <li>Then to generate a prediction of this country's happiness, we put these inputs into the decision tree, which hands us back its best prediction. </li>
          <li>And all that's left is to display the result to the webpage!</li>
        </ol>
      </p>

